<section id="episode-background" class="level2">
<h2 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="episode-background">Episode Background</h2>
<section id="introducing-mindmeld-and-notebooklm-an-ai-powered-audio-experience" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="introducing-mindmeld-and-notebooklm-an-ai-powered-audio-experience">Introducing MindMeld and NotebookLM: An AI-Powered Audio Experience</h3>
<p>In this inaugural episode, I’m introducing the MindMeld website and its first three blog posts using NotebookLM, a powerful AI tool developed by Google. NotebookLM helps users understand and summarize texts while generating podcast-like audio content that’s accessible to the general public.</p>
<p>I first discovered NotebookLM on Twitter, where it was highlighted as a tool for making academic research more accessible by transforming complex papers into formats that general audiences can understand.</p>
</section>
<section id="notebooklms-evolution" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="notebooklms-evolution">NotebookLM’s Evolution</h3>
<p>NotebookLM has been available since at least 2023, with its audio overview feature launching on September 11, 2024. When I began using it in July 2024, the platform was still in beta, requiring users to join a waitlist for access. The initial version I experienced would create podcast-like audio content featuring two virtual hosts who would summarize texts while attempting to make the content relatable through casual conversation and examples. This approach sometimes led to interesting results:</p>
<ul>
<li>Hosts occasionally strayed from the main topic</li>
<li>Some interpretations of the text weren’t entirely accurate</li>
<li>Simple inputs could trigger surprisingly deep analysis (which was quite entertaining to hear)</li>
</ul>
</section>
<section id="recent-updates-and-customization" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="recent-updates-and-customization">Recent Updates and Customization</h3>
<p>While the early version didn’t identify the hosts and simply launched into their “own” podcast format, the latest version includes a context/prompt window for customization. According to the site’s guidelines, users can:</p>
<ul>
<li>Focus on specific sources when multiple are provided</li>
<li>Highlight particular topics</li>
<li>Target specific audiences</li>
<li>Add personal touches (like greeting specific people)</li>
<li>Override the default introduction</li>
</ul>
</section>
<section id="the-mindmeld-experience" class="level3">
<h3 class="anchored" data-anchor-id="the-mindmeld-experience">The MindMeld Experience</h3>
<p>For this episode, I used NotebookLM to generate audio content from MindMeld’s first three blog posts. I successfully prompted the hosts to introduce the podcast as “MindMeld Podcasts” and acknowledge their status as virtual hosts.</p>
<p>However, several interesting challenges emerged during this experiment:</p>
<ol type="1">
<li>Despite customization attempts, the hosts sometimes reverted to calling the podcast “DeepDive”</li>
<li>Certain content was repeated unnecessarily</li>
<li>The system doesn’t recognize text formatting like strikethrough, leading to some misinterpretations</li>
<li>Even when prompted about the site’s AI-generated nature, the hosts attributed much of the content and reviews to FRA</li>
</ol>
<p>Despite these limitations, the tool offers an intriguing way to transform written content into engaging audio formats.</p>
</section>
</section>
